title: For Sale:  Egyptian Helwan 9mm pistol w/ 120 rounds of Egyptian 9mm Ammo
postcontent:
Egyptian Helwan 9mm pistol w/ 120 rounds of Egyptian 9mm Ammo and 1 magazine. The Helwan is the Egyptian copy of the Berretta M1951 Brigadier that was licensed to the Maadi arms factory in Egypt. The pistol is best described as a smaller, single stack version of the Berretta 92. This pistol has all the original Egyptian (Arabic) markings on the slide, above the trigger, as well as on the barrel. The barrel is also threaded.

This is the same pattern pistol as the Iraqi Tariq, so if you have set of bringback grips they would make this look pretty cool. I've only used the pistol for display with all our other trinkets from times when when my wife and I have been to the Middle East and aside from firing it once when I bought it, it's sat unused for several years. The only issue with this pistol is that the barrel lock block is a little snug, common for these pistols, so sometimes it takes "man strength" to rack the slide manually. The ammo is Egyptian surplus, with Arabic markings on the rounds and box labels, that I randomly acquired a few backs. All in all I think it's a neat little gun that helps to fill the niche left by us not being able to bring back weapons from Iraq/Afghanistan like people used to during Vietnam/WW2.

No trades wanted, willing to ship to an FFL for an extra $25.

title: For Sale:  Enfield Jungle Carbine
postcontent:
I have an original 1946 Enfield No5 MK1 (F) Jungle Carbine, .303 British, that is in excellent condition for its age.  Its in better condition than the ones I see on Armslist that are listed for more than my price.  It is numbers matching on the bolt, receiver and stock.  It has flip up adjustable sights and shoots well.  Made in the Royal Ordnance Factory Fazakerley, Liverpool.  The guy I got it from a couple years ago was a collector and he said he had never shot it.  I test fired it maybe 10 shots to see that it worked then put it away.  

Before shooting I took it apart to verify that it was original and not a copy.  The No.5  had additional metal shaved away from the barrel, the underside, left, and right sides of the receiver when manufactured.  This additional milling is the gold standard of identification for a true No.5 carbine and not a fake and the milling was there so it checked good.  I then cleaned it out and the barrel was full of a green grease that smelled like real old web gear.  The rifling looks brand new and I'm curious that it may have never been shot when I got it.  I have one bandolier with rounds on stripper clips minus the few that I shot.  

I have a CCL and would like the purchaser to have a CCL to show they care legit to own this.  We will write up a bill of sale/transfer of rifle.  Don't offer me junk in trade or a low ball offer I don't need to sell it and it doesn't take a lot of room up in my safe.  I just don't use it so would rather have something I would use.

Would trade for an AK, nice carry gun, .44mag, Remington 700, model 1911 .45

title: For Sale:  FLIR Scout PS32 Thermal Night Vision Monocular
postcontent:
I'm selling a FLIR Scout PS32 that I purchased last Christmas.  I have used it for a total of maybe 5 hours and it's in like-new condition, with the original box and all accessories.  If you're not familiar with thermal, it's almost magical in it's ability to see in complete darkness, and specifically to pick out the heat signatures of animals.  Check out the link below for a good overview.  I'm not looking to trade anything for this.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VUDlaZ2U-Go

From the manufacturer:
The compact, lightweight FLIR Scout PS32 provides clear, crisp thermal imagery from dawn to dusk and through the dead of night. It fits easily and naturally into the palm of your hand and features simplified operation making it an ideal choice for sportsmen, hikers, ranchers, rangers, or backyard nature enthusiasts. If you can’t bear to miss a thing while exploring the great outdoors, the Scout PS32 thermal imager is a great entry-level device.

Like all FLIR thermal imagers, the Scout PS32 creates images from heat, not light, giving you a tactical advantage out in the wild. You can navigate rough terrain to scope out the “perfect spot” at dusk, before dawn and even when it’s pitch black outside. You can discover nocturnal animals, find wandering members of your party, locate lost livestock or spot downed game. You can use Scout to help see through light fog, smoke or trail dust and even use it to help insulate your home, check out things that go bump in the night, and much more.

The FLIR Scout PS32 has been long-awaited. Its compact form factor fits in the palm of your hand and its price tag makes it the most affordable thermal imager in its class. In fact, the PS32 costs less and performs better than its competition. The unit is easily carried and fits in most cargo pockets. The lightweight housing is easy to hold up for extended periods of time. Controls are laid out across the top of the unit (except for a focus knob on the side) and are easy to access in the dark. No menus to scroll through or confusing buttons. The PS32 is a no-frills device. It is a thermal imager only – no camera, no weapon mount, etc. This helps to keep the cost, size, and weight to a minimum. It uses an internal, rechargeable battery that charges via an included USB cable.

The performance of the PS32 is great for the price. Its 320×240 sensor allows detection of animals out to about 500 yards. Resolution is crisp and allows you to see definition in the gray scale. Also included is FLIR’s proprietary “Instalert” mode that shades moving objects in red. We were able to literally, plug and play with the PS32. The pictograms on the buttons are no-brainers and a quick look at them allowed us to get started. The housing is comfortable to hold and extremely lightweight.

The PS32 has all the same features as the PS24, but has an upgraded 320×240 sensor and an added 2x electronic zoom.

Make: Marlin 

Model: Model 782 

Serial Number: 19779238

Year of Manufacture: 1977 

Caliber: .22 W.M.R. (Winchester Magnum Rimfire) 

Action Type: Bolt Action Rifle, w/ Detachable Box Magazine 

Markings: The left side of the barrel is marked "THE MARLIN FIREARMS CO. NORTH HAVEN, CT. U.S.A. / MODEL 782 -- MICRO-GROOVE BARREL -- CAL. 22 W.M.R. ONLY", and has a "JM" contained in an oval. The left side of the receiver is marked "19779238". The right side of the barrel is marked with the safety "warning". 

Barrel Length: 22" 

Sights / Optics: This rifle is mounted with a brass bead post style front sight dovetailed into a ramp, with a detachable hood. The rear sight is the standard fold down semi-buckhorn with elevator. The receiver is grooved to take clamp on scope mounts. Scope attached is a Tasco 4x15, perfect for sighting varmints and small game. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The one piece stock is WALNUT (not a laminate or picture of walnut ), with impressed checkering on the pistol grip and the forearm areas. The comb of the butt stock is Monte Carlo style and there is a Marlin hard black plastic butt plate with white spacer. The stock is fitted with sling swivels, sling is attached, and has the traditional Marlin "Bullseye". The LOP measures 13 ¾" from the front of the trigger to the rear of the butt stock. The stock has no chips or cracks and no marks. The stocks rate in about EXCELLENT PLUS overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Blue 

Finish Originality: All Original 

Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the Micro-Groove rifling is sharp. There is NO erosion, DEEP BLUING is as it was purchased originally, the muzzle crown is unmarked. 

Overall Condition: This rifle retains about 99% of its metal finish. The balance of the finish shows wear at the sharp edge of the scope mounts. The Screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. Overall, this rifle rates in about EXCELLENT PLUS condition. 

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. Rifle has been fired about 50 rounds, 30+ years ago, and will hit a dime, dead center, at 100 yards. Cleaned and oiled every 6 months for 37 years. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: An official Marlin leather carrying sling is provided. The sling is in Fine condition with only a few scuff or compression marks. There is also one unmarked magazine which functions correctly. Also comes with a Weather Shield tan leather carry case, model # 1291, Made in the U.S.A., also in EXCELLENT condition.

Assessment: This Marlin looks as if it may never have been fired, but since it was, I can not sell it as new. Purchased just after return from Vietnam and stored it very carefully in a humidity controlled display case in Michigan with other collectables. This rifle appears "like new". Chambered in .22 W.M.R. this rifle is an excellent gun for pests or small varmint control, particularly when out fitted with a scope.  This rifle will make a fine present for a young man learning to shoot with the best rifle he will ever own, or for a collection piece of Marlin Rifle history. You will be impressed with the condition of this 37 year old perfect rifle!! Send me your best offer, I will consider all reasonable offers.
